1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1350–1454":"1350–1454","–1444":"–1444","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, England","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Leighton or Layton. Most, as for example those in Bedfordshire, Cambridgeshire, Cheshire, Lancashire, and Shropshire, are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, but Layton in Durham derives from Old English <i>ge-lād</i> ‘road’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English pronunciation of <i>Leighton</i> is usually /lɛ:tən/ or /leitən/ (also spelled   Layton   and   Leaton  ), but it can also be heard as /laitən/ or as /li:tən/ (also spelled   Leaton  ), and occasionally as /lɛtən/ (spelled   Letton  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Layton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Slayton","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Leighton   (compare   Layton  ) with the addition of initial <i>S-</i>. Alternatively, perhaps a variant of   Sladen   or of <b>Sleightholme</b>, principally a habitational name from Sleightholme Dale in Kirkbymoorside, but perhaps occasionally from Sleightholme in Bowes or the lost Sleightholme in Lythe. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>sléttr</i> ‘smooth, level’ + <i>holmr</i> ‘small island, water meadow’. This surname is now very rare in Britain. Compare   Slaydon  ."]},{"name":"Leaton","meanings":["English: variant of   Leighton  ."]},{"name":"Laughton","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Laughton en le Morthen in Yorkshire, Laughton in Leicestershire or any of the two places called Laughton in Lincolnshire (one near Gainsborough and another near Folkingham). The places are named with Old English <i>lēac</i> ‘leek’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure’, meaning ‘village or farm where leeks are grown’. It may sometimes have alternated with   Leighton  , which is mostly from placenames with the same etymology.","variant of   Lawton  ."]},{"name":"Letton","meanings":["English: habitational name, most probably from Letton in Norfolk or Latton in Essex. It could also be a variant of   Leighton   or   Laughton  . Most of the places so named have the same etymology as Letton and Latton, i.e. ‘farm where leeks are grown’ (Old English <i>lēac-tūn</i>). Another possibility is that it is a variant of   Latten  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":80,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Leighton was born in 1375, in Leighton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Edward Leighton and Elizabeth Stapleton. He married Margareta Drake in 1400, in Church Stretton, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Church Stretton, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"1375–":"1375–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1350–1454":"1350–1454","–1444":"–1444","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, England","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1375–":"1375–Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1350–1454":"1350–1454","–1444":"–1444","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shropshire, England","Leighton, Shropshire, England":"Leighton, Shropshire, England"},"fr":{"1375–":"1375–Décédé","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1390–1419":"1390–1419","1412–1456":"1412–1456","1350–1454":"1350–1454","–1444":"–1444","1412":"1412","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1444":"1444","1454":"1454","1375":"1375","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1419":"1419","1390":"1390","Church Stretton, Shropshire, England":"Church Stretton, Shro